Pretty printing a complex object does not really work...
``` python

from munch import munchify
from pprint import pprint

a = {
  "a": [1, 2, 3],
  "b": {
    "inner": {
      "inner-inner": [1, 2, 3],
      "inner-inner2": [1, 2, 3],
      "inner-inner3": [1, 2, 3],
    },
    "second-inner": "asdfasdf",
  },
  "c": {
    "inner": {
      "inner-inner": [1, 2, 3],
      "inner-inner2": [1, 2, 3],
      "inner-inner3": [1, 2, 3],
    },
    "second-inner": "asdfasdf",
  }
}
pprint(munchify(a))
```
Results in:
``` python
Munch("{'a': [1, 2, 3], 'c': {'second-inner': 'asdfasdf', 'inner': {'inner-inner': [1, 2, 3], 'inner-inner3': [1, 2, 3], 'inner-inner2': [1, 2, 3]}}, 'b': {'second-inner': 'asdfasdf', 'inner': {'inner-inner': [1, 2, 3], 'inner-inner3': [1, 2, 3], 'inner-inner2': [1, 2, 3]}}}")
```

If I define an object that inherits from Munch:

class Foo(Munch):
    def __init__(self, bar):
       self.bar = bar

and then do:

myfoo = Foo("mybar")

the resulting myfoo object has no __dict__ attribute, so while I can do myfoo.toDict(), I can't do myfoo.__dict__ which would be nice to allow it to be treated like any other object.

@property
def __dict__(self):
    return self.toDict()

would allow myfoo.__dict__ to work the same way as toDict()
